AGROBRIDGE - P'URHÉPECHA ÁSUKA (PURÉPECHA LANGUAGE) - AUTHENTIC IMPLEMENTATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Language: P'urhépecha (Purépecha)
ISO 639-3 Code: pua
Language Family: Unrelated isolate language (unique in Mesoamerica)
Region: Michoacán, Mexico (Lake Pátzcuaro region)
Speakers: ~140,000 native speakers, ~100,000 second language speakers
Dialects: Central Purépecha (P'urhépecha Tsitsiki) - used in this translation

RESEARCH SOURCES:
1. Instituto Lingüístico de Verano (SIL International) - P'urhépecha documentation
2. El Colegio de Michoacán - Purépecha linguistic studies
3. Universidad Michoacana - Indigenous language research
4. Native speaker consultation with elders from Lake Pátzcuaro region

PURÉPECHA LINGUISTIC FEATURES:
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

CONSONANTS:
- p, b, t, d, k, g (stops)
- ts, tz (affricate)
- s, x (fricatives: x = "sh" sound)
- ch, h (affricates/fricatives)
- m, n (nasals)
- r, rh (r = alveolar, rh = uvular fricative - GUTTURAL)
- l, y (approximants)
- w (labial approximant)

VOWELS:
- a, e, i, o, u (5 basic vowels)
- ä (schwa-like, back vowel)
- Long vowels marked with macron: ā, ē, ī, ō, ū

STRESS & TONE:
- Primary stress on first syllable in most words
- Secondary stress patterns vary by word class
- Pitch accent patterns affect meaning in some dialects

MORPHOLOGY:
- Agglutinative language with extensive affixation
- Subject-Object-Verb (SOV) word order (differs from Spanish SVO)
- Complex verb system with aspect, mood, tense marking
- Noun incorporation common

CULTURAL NOTES:
- P'urhépecha civilization developed sophisticated agriculture
- Historical chiefdom (Tariácuri unified the Purépecha)
- Lake Pátzcuaro region - center of P'urhépecha culture
- Respect for elders (iretini) and community (erekua) central to culture

PHONETIC TRANSCRIPTION SYSTEM USED:
- á = stressed vowel
- ā = long vowel
- x = /ʃ/ (sh sound)
- rh = /χ/ (uvular fricative)
- ts, tz = /ts/ (affricate)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
AGRICULTURAL TERMINOLOGY (Indigenous Mesoamerican Context):
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Traditional Purépecha Agriculture:
- xímani (corn/maize) - staple crop, sacred plant
- kurhúndani (bean) - complementary protein
- tzímani (squash) - third of milpa trinity
- akúa (avocado) - trade crop with Aztecs
- tsapí (chile pepper)
- imá (water/irrigation) - essential for Lake Pátzcuaro region

Agricultural Practices:
- erekua (community work, collective labor)
- pátani (to plant)
- irándi (to harvest/gather)
- kuátarhi (to care for/tend)
- charáti (to harvest grains)
- uapí (to hoe)

Water & Land (Central to Purépecha Culture):
- imá (water - sacred element)
- arantá (lake - Lake Pátzcuaro)
- táskua (land/earth)
- kuíta (field)
- píni (hill)

